<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920129-0043</DOCNO><DOCID>920129-0043.</DOCID><HL>   Furon to Restructure   And Post a Big Charge   For Fiscal 4th Quarter</HL><DATE>01/29/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9</SO><CO>   FCBN</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>DIVERSIFIED INDUSTRIAL (IDD)</IN><NS>EARNINGS PROJECTIONS (ERP)RESTRUCTURINGS, RECAPITALIZATION (RCN)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   LAGUNA NIGUEL, Calif. -- Furon Co. said it will divestitself of six of its 23 businesses in a restructuring thatwill produce a pretax charge of between $27 million and $32million for the fourth quarter ending Feb. 1.   The charge of roughly $2.49 to $2.96 a share will resultin a net loss for the quarter and year, the company said.Furon reported net income of $1.3 million, or 16 cents ashare, in the year-earlier quarter and net of $9.1 million,or $1.17 a share, for fiscal 1991.</LP><TEXT>   J. Michael Hagan, chairman and chief executive officer,said the six targeted companies have annual sales of about$42 million, or about 14% of Furon's total volume. Furonmakes components of specialized polymer materials for theindustrial market, and serves several industries includingpetrochemical, aerospace, medical transportation andpollution control.   The earmarked companies are FO-MAC of Tulsa, Okla.; IER ofTwinsburg, Ohio; Grover Piston Ring of Milwaukee; StructuralBearings of Athens, Texas; Filtration Products of Houston;and Reynolds and Taylor of Santa Ana, Calif. Mr. Hagan saidhe hopes to have those divestitures completed by the end of1992.   The restructuring will leave Furon with businesses thathave proprietary materials or processing technologies thatwill likely produce better long-term returns, Mr. Hagan said.</TEXT></DOC>